{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564854"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:19:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:19:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17156"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17156","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17156"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.57,0.24,0.05,0.01,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9846"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68814"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9846"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17156"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54271"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4384"},{"type":"tags","id":"4520"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12080"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23072"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43686"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68814"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 26-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for her first antenatal review at 12 weeks gestation. She works as a kindergarten teacher and has a three-year-old child at home. This is her second pregnancy. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy vitamins. Routine antenatal screening reveals cytomegalovirus (CMV) IgM positive, IgG positive with low IgG avidity.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate advice regarding this pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Referral for detailed ultrasound assessment and amniocentesis","Repeat serology in four weeks","Termination of pregnancy","Change of occupation until delivery","Reassurance and routine antenatal care"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s serology suggests primary CMV infection within the past 3-4 months. The combination of positive IgM, positive IgG, and low IgG avidity is diagnostic of recent primary infection. Given she is 12 weeks pregnant, this likely occurred in early pregnancy or just before conception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral for detailed ultrasound assessment and amniocentesis\u003C/strong\u003E is appropriate as primary CMV infection in early pregnancy carries a 30-40% risk of congenital infection. Amniocentesis (performed after 20 weeks) can detect fetal infection, while detailed ultrasound can identify characteristic features of congenital CMV such as microcephaly, intracerebral calcifications, or hydrops.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance and routine antenatal care\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate given the high risk of congenital infection and potential serious sequelae. This requires specialist follow-up and detailed fetal assessment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETermination of pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E would be premature at this stage without confirming fetal infection or identifying serious abnormalities. Many infected fetuses have normal outcomes, and the decision regarding continuation of pregnancy should be based on confirmed findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChange of occupation\u003C/strong\u003E would not affect the current pregnancy as infection has already occurred. However, good hand hygiene should be discussed for future pregnancies given her occupational exposure risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat serology in four weeks\u003C/strong\u003E would not add useful information as the diagnosis of primary infection is already established. The focus should be on assessing fetal impact rather than maternal serology.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Low CMV IgG avidity with positive IgM suggests primary CMV infection within the past 3-4 months.","Primary CMV infection in early pregnancy carries a 30-40% risk of congenital infection.","Occupational exposure to young children increases the risk of CMV infection during pregnancy."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Management of perinatal infections: a consensus statement [Internet]. Melbourne (AU): RANZCOG; 2014 [cited 2024 Dec 10]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/ASID-Management-of-Perinatal-Infections.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54271"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17156"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54271","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54271"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T15:59:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T16:00:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9846"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68814"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","